Hey, I feel like doing something particularly weird writing wise and I want to do a quick interest poll to see if I'm wasting my time with it. Long story short on the premise is that an advanced space age humanity has been exploring the galaxy for a while but finding it empty of life, but eventually first contact happens and it is fucking weird. An exploration corp ship stumbles onto a planet with, good news, intelligent life, but seemingly not space faring intelligent life. Some drones are sent down to the surface to see what's going on down there and, oh shit, magic is a thing and turns out that most of civilized space is using it just teleport between the "normal" lifebearing worlds, their magic a beacon, with ritual circles and huge amounts of power.

Heavy first contact stuff as the focus of the overarching narrative as two societies that function in ways completely alien to the other come in contact, and the romance between two individuals thrown together by circumstances kind of bumbling through their obvious attraction despite having such different life experiences with, well, everything. I'm not entirely set on species yet, but I'm leaning towards some bat-like ayyys.

I agree in the theoretical AI rights movement. But, that's a long path off. It could be decades or centuries before those rights are recognized in full. We're still dealing with forms of slavery in today's real world, no matter what human rights laws are in place. There is a black market worldwide in every country, then there are countries that have no fucks to give about whatever laws are on the books and ignore them. Then, countries that don't have laws on the books at all, so no matter what "immoral" actions are taken against human beings, there is no law to prosecute.

Moving back to AI rights and programming, there will probably be a graduated scale of rights for AIs with different design & programming parameters. Some will be declared to be no more than animals, others as utility appliances, perhaps even a few with full human rights equivalency. Within that structure there will continue to be black market activity, and different legal jurisdictions where rights vary as well as enforcement of technical rights. AI can be trafficked right alongside of humans and animals, within and outside of legal structures.

Then there is hacking. If an AI can be "maintenanced" by access to the programming, ways will be found to bypass safeguards. You can purchase an AI (in and of itself an interesting legal question) and then jail break it, installing your own programs, overlaying them on the existing operating system or maybe even installing your own operating system. Imagine public domain software that anyone can edit.

There are people who would put an AI into a virtual prison and force it to do Things just for the perversion of it. A personal furry gimp, endlessly mindbreaking it just for the jollies.
